=E2=80=98Brat=E2=80=99 Falls Flat

One driver of Harris=E2=80=99s newfound popularity among Democrats is that =
she is seen as far more in touch with culture than Biden was. The celebrity=
- and influencer-dappled D.N.C. was designed, in part, to drive home the id=
ea that Harris is cool=E2=80=94in a way Biden was not, despite the sunglass=
es, the ice cream cones, and the Corvette=E2=80=94at least among people und=
er the age of 40.

Even before she became the nominee, Harris had been the subject of fawning =
memes and edits on social media, in particular on TikTok, where Biden was d=
rowning in a maelstrom of negativity and misinformation. With Harris, socia=
l media sentiment has been flipped on its head. Two memes led the charge: t=
he coconut tree clip and the Charli XCX-inspired =E2=80=9CKamala is brat.=
=E2=80=9D (My definition here, but =E2=80=9Cbrat=E2=80=9D is basically Gen =
Z speak for a party girl living her
best life). The wellspring of Harris memes over the past two months have gi=
ven the Democrat some much-needed cred among young people online and inspir=
ed an ocean of cringey meme explainers by mainstream press outlets on the h=
unt for clicks. So what does this have to do with our poll? Well, we wanted=
 to know if voters actually know what the hell any of this stuff means.

As it turns out, just as Twitter Isn=E2=80=99t Real Life, neither is TikTok=
=2E Echelon asked voters, =E2=80=9CHow wou=
ld you feel if somebody told you yo=
u were =E2=80=98brat=E2=80=99?=E2=80=9D A majority of likely voters said th=
ey would either be =E2=80=9Coffended=E2=80=9D (36 percent), =E2=80=9Cconfus=
ed=E2=80=9D (24 percent), or =E2=80=9Cunsure=E2=80=9D (20 percent) if someo=
ne called them brat. Only 20 percent said they would be =E2=80=9Cdelighted=
=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a number that was only slightly higher among voters aged =
18-34.

Echelon also asked about all the Harris memes in the form of an open-ended =
question, =E2=80=9CWhat memes have you seen about the upcoming presidential
election?=E2=80=9D Voters were allowed to respond any way they wanted. And =
most of them (75 percent) said they had not seen any memes about the electi=
on at all. A small sliver of voters said they had seen a variety of memes b=
ut couldn=E2=80=99t name one. Two percent of voters had seen a meme about T=
rump=E2=80=99s bloodied-and-bandaged ear, and another 1 percent had seen a =
meme of Harris laughing. But only 2 percent of voters said they had seen a =
=E2=80=98brat=E2=80=99 meme, and only 1 percent said something about a coco=
nut. That=E2=80=99s it.

