          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Last Tuesday at the=
 Democratic National Convention in Chicago, as I was getting mic=E2=80=99d =
up for a segment on CNN=E2=80=99s <i>Inside Politics</i> with <b>Dana</b> <=
b>Bash</b>, I glanced up at the massive screen above the speaker=E2=80=99s =
podium and almost spat out my coffee. The convention producers were doing s=
ound checks and toggling through that night=E2=80=99s slogans, one of which=
, in giant all-caps letters, was =E2=80=9CCountry First.=E2=80=9D Dana and =
I both chuckled. The two of us were on <b>John</b> <b>McCain</b>=E2=80=99s =
campaign bus back in 2008, when that was <i>McCain</i>=E2=80=99s slogan, a =
cudgel deployed by the Vietnam War hero against his liberal, antiwar oppone=
nt, <b>Barack Obama</b>. <br/><br/>Republicans, after all, are usually the =
ones wrapping themselves in the American flag. But now it=E2=80=99s <b>Kama=
la Harris</b>, the newly ordained Democratic nominee, who=E2=80=99s running
as the tough patriot. In her telling, it=E2=80=99s <b>Donald Trump</b> who =
would roll back our freedoms, cater to dictators, and undermine the Constit=
ution. =E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=9CAs president, I will never waver in defen=
se of America=E2=80=99s security and ideals, because in the enduring strugg=
le between democracy and tyranny, I know where I stand and I know where the=
 United States belongs,=E2=80=9D Harris declared in her address on Thursday=
 night. =E2=80=9CFellow Americans,=E2=80=9D she continued, =E2=80=9CI love =
our country with all my heart.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Yes, this was a Democrat =
talking. There were paeans to diversity and pluralism, of course, vows to p=
rotect abortion rights and stand up to big corporations. But Harris, and th=
e many speakers in both parties who came before her, also promised to maint=
ain the =E2=80=9Cmost lethal=E2=80=9D military on Earth, to shore up the br=
oken U.S.-Mexico border, and to protect the meritocratic American dream. Un=
like 2020, when she stumbled through a Democratic primary in which everyone=
 was racing
to the left, Harris=E2=80=99s audience last week was not Bushwick or Burlin=
gton. It was the suburban middle. The deciders. <br/><br/>Harris campaign s=
trategists, very much aware that plenty of voters still think the Democrati=
c nominee is too liberal, are trying to bury those concerns, and unabashedl=
y playing to win. Harris=E2=80=99s flip-flops on issues she once supported=
=E2=80=94Medicare for All, abolishing I.C.E., banning fracking=E2=80=94are =
absolutely brazen. And so far, Democrats don=E2=80=99t seem to care. Indepe=
ndents don=E2=80=99t seem to, either, according to polls. And party insider=
s who are sick of genuflecting to the left? They=E2=80=99re as hyped as the=
y=E2=80=99ve been in years. As one Democratic strategist texted me Friday a=
fter the convention: =E2=80=9CForeign policy hawks like me fucking <i>ate</=
i> at that convention.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>A new survey from Echelon Insights=
, which is partnering with Puck for exclusive polling on the 2024 electorat=
e, suggests that the tolerant-but-tough message is working. In one of the
few surveys conducted entirely after the D.N.C., a poll of likely voters co=
nducted from Friday to Sunday found Harris running about even with Trump on=
 a range of attributes that previously favored the Republican nominee. On t=
he question of which candidate is =E2=80=9Ca strong leader,=E2=80=9D Trump =
leads Harris by only one point, 48 percent to 47 percent. Who would do bett=
er at =E2=80=9Ckeeping the country safe=E2=80=9D? Again, Trump leads by one=
 point, 47-46. =E2=80=9CGood at managing a crisis=E2=80=9D? They=E2=80=99re=
 tied, 46-46. Harris is also trailing Trump by only a single point (48-47) =
on the question of which candidate =E2=80=9Cwould make our economy work bet=
ter.=E2=80=9D On pretty much every single question about strength or toughn=
ess=E2=80=94and on questions where Republicans might typically lead=E2=80=
=94Harris has essentially erased <b>Joe Biden</b>=E2=80=99s deficits agains=
t Trump.  <br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s more evidence, I=E2=80=99d argue, that v=
oters were seeing Biden almost entirely through the lens of his advanced ag=
e. But it also suggests
that the Harris campaign was smart to address public concerns about her rec=
ord on immigration and border security out of the gate, with an early paid =
media campaign portraying her as a tough-on-crime prosecutor. Voters in the=
 Echelon poll were asked to name the most important attribute in deciding t=
heir vote. The top answer was =E2=80=9Ca strong leader,=E2=80=9D with 24 pe=
rcent of voters citing it as their top attribute. It might have been unthin=
kable two months ago, but Harris has neutralized Trump=E2=80=99s advantage =
on the strength question.<br/><br/>Meanwhile, Harris is far outrunning Trum=
p on the attributes that you=E2=80=99d expect. By wide margins, Harris is s=
een as more =E2=80=9Chonest and trustworthy=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnormal.=
=E2=80=9D She=E2=80=99s winning on =E2=80=9Chaving the right temperament=E2=
=80=9D by 12 points, and on the question of =E2=80=9Ccares about people lik=
e me=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a useful bellwether in most elections=E2=80=94Harris =
is leading Trump by five points. On these topics, too, Harris is performing=
 much better than Biden was
when he was the nominee. <br/></td>
