          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">One driver of Harri=
s=E2=80=99s newfound popularity among Democrats is that she is seen as far =
more in touch with culture than Biden was. The celebrity- and influencer-da=
ppled D.N.C. was designed, in part, to drive home the idea that Harris is <=
i>cool</i>=E2=80=94in a way Biden was not, despite the sunglasses, the ice =
cream cones, and the Corvette=E2=80=94at least among people under the age o=
f 40. <br/><br/>Even before she became the nominee, Harris had been the sub=
ject of fawning memes and edits on social media, in particular on TikTok, w=
here Biden was drowning in a maelstrom of negativity and misinformation. Wi=
th Harris, social media sentiment has been flipped on its head. Two memes l=
ed the charge: the coconut tree clip and the <b>Charli XCX</b>-inspired =E2=
=80=9CKamala is brat.=E2=80=9D (My definition here, but =E2=80=9Cbrat=E2=80=
=9D is basically Gen Z speak for a party girl living her
best life). The wellspring of Harris memes over the past two months have gi=
ven the Democrat some much-needed cred among young people online and inspir=
ed an ocean of cringey meme explainers by mainstream press outlets on the h=
unt for clicks. So what does this have to do with our poll? Well, we wanted=
 to know if voters actually know what the hell any of this stuff means. <br=
/><br/>As it turns out, just as Twitter Isn=E2=80=99t Real Life, neither is=
 TikTok. Echelon asked voters, =E2=80=9CHow would you feel if somebody told=
 you you were =E2=80=98brat=E2=80=99?=E2=80=9D A majority of likely voters =
said they would either be =E2=80=9Coffended=E2=80=9D (36 percent), =E2=80=
=9Cconfused=E2=80=9D (24 percent), or =E2=80=9Cunsure=E2=80=9D (20 percent)=
 if someone called them brat. Only 20 percent said they would be =E2=80=9Cd=
elighted=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94a number that was only slightly higher among vote=
rs aged 18-34. <br/><br/>Echelon also asked about all the Harris memes in t=
he form of an open-ended question, =E2=80=9CWhat memes have you seen about =
the upcoming presidential
election?=E2=80=9D Voters were allowed to respond any way they wanted. And =
most of them (75 percent) said they had not seen any memes about the electi=
on at all. A small sliver of voters said they had seen a variety of memes b=
ut couldn=E2=80=99t name one. Two percent of voters had seen a meme about T=
rump=E2=80=99s bloodied-and-bandaged ear, and another 1 percent had seen a =
meme of Harris laughing. But only 2 percent of voters said they had seen a =
=E2=80=98brat=E2=80=99 meme, and only 1 percent said something about a coco=
nut. That=E2=80=99s it.<br/><br/>In other words, if you know what =E2=80=9C=
brat=E2=80=9D means, you live in a very small cultural bubble populated by =
other screen addicts. And in the waning days of this brat summer, maybe you=
 should consider logging off for a day, removing your AirPods, and planning=
 a leisurely road trip to the nearest Bass Pro Shops, where you can learn a=
 little more about your fellow Americans, in service of the good citizenshi=
p Harris was calling for in Chicago. <br/></td>
         </tr>
